 Unpopular opinion:
Most developers are building on a foundation they completely misunderstand.
And it's going to cost them.

Let me say something that might annoy a few people.
ChatGPT is not an agent.
It never was.
And if you're a developer who's been calling it one — you've been thinking about AI the wrong way this whole time.
I was too. Until I actually sat down and understood the difference.

Here's the simplest way I can put it:
ChatGPT is a brilliant friend you can ask anything.
An agent is an employee you give a job to — and they go finish it.
One answers.
The other acts.
That's not a small distinction.
That's everything.

A real example:
You ask ChatGPT:
"What should I do if my Aave position is close to liquidation?"
It tells you. Beautifully. With steps.
You still have to go do it yourself.

You give an agent the same job:
It checks your health factor.
Detects the risk.
Tops up your collateral.
Sends you a confirmation.
While you were sleeping.

The technical difference is 3 things:
1. Memory
ChatGPT forgets you the moment the chat ends.
An agent remembers context across sessions — it knows what happened last time.
2. Tools
ChatGPT talks about doing things.
An agent has actual tools — APIs, wallets, contracts — that it uses.
3. Loop
ChatGPT responds once and stops.
An agent runs in a loop — Observe, Reason, Act — until the task is complete.
One is a conversation.
The other is a process.

Why this matters for you as a developer:
If you're building a "ChatGPT wrapper" and calling it an AI product —
You're not building a product.
You're building a chatbot with good PR.
The real opportunity — the one that's still wide open — is autonomous systems.
Agents that hold wallets.
Agents that monitor protocols.
Agents that execute on-chain without waiting for a human to press a button.
That's the building frontier right now.
And blockchain developers are — quietly — the most positioned people to build it.
Because we already think in systems.
We already think in permissions.
We already think in what happens if this goes wrong.

That's not a coincidence.
That's an edge.

